            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> > ```\r\n> > {\r\n> >   \".git\",\r\n> >   type = \"directory\",\r\n> > },\r\n> > ```\r\n> \r\n> Sorry for the drive-by comment, but searching for '.git' as both directory and file is better in most cases. A file '.git' is used in Git submodules to indicate its project root. Just please don't use this as an example in documentation.\r\n\r\nUsually yes, and it will stay the default behaviour.\r\n\r\nBut in somes cases, the upper `.git` folder may me more interesting to search for.\r\n\r\nI usually work with one main git directory, with multiple sub-levels of submodules.\r\nIn that case, when searching from any of the sub-sub-module files, I would like to search for the top-level .git folder, hence searching for the \"directory\" one.\r\nI use this for example for my formatter or the automatic ctags generation.\r\n\r\nThe idea is to let the user choose, with default values searching for \"files\" and \"directories\", like now.",
