            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> Thank you for the contribution. I think we'd definitely need documentation on what these \"types\" could even be both in the PR here and in the corresponding documentation of `vim.fs.root()` (see the docs and how to update them with `make`).\r\n> \r\n> A question for you: what are these \"types\"? if there is only \"folder\" and \"file\", what do you think about having a trailing slash appended to the argument as implying the \"folder\" type, entirely bypassing the need for an argument? 🤔 I'm not too sure of analogous pre-existing patterns here but it does come across as quite simple & elegant to me intuitively.\r\n\r\nThe documentation will be done correctly, with examples, obviously.\r\nI wanted to have some first draft feedback before committing to make the documentation.\r\nIf the feedback is \"maybe, let's see, who knows...?\" or something, I will do the work correctly. \r\n\r\nThe variable can search for \"directories\", \"files\" , but also \"link\" (by reading the function `vim.fs.find`.\r\n\r\nThe idea was to bubble-up one level the capabilities of the `vim.fs.find` function.\r\nThere is no \"new\" idea or pattern, I \"only\" copied the ones in the `vim.fs.find`.\r\n\r\nRegarding the linting of the variables, I will have to search how to extend the signature documentation with the `---@type ... something` to force the linter not to complain.",
